Exploring the Golf Digest and Golf Magazine Rankings

Every two years, Golf Digest and Golf Magazine issue widely read and debated rankings of the nation’s best golf courses. This has been a decades-long undertaking - Golf Digest has released rankings from #1 to #100 since 1985, while Golf Digest followed suit starting in 1991. (Golf Digest has actually been in this game even longer than that - before 1985 they grouped courses into First 10 through Fifth 10 and the Second 50, which makes more sense but doesn’t sell as many magazines.)

Ranking golf courses, like ranking colleges, is both a fool’s errand and a natural instinct, a pointless exercise as well as a major feather in the cap for courses across the country. Golfers can’t help but compare and contrast the courses they have played, and those comparisons can be quantified and sorted. Thanks to numerical rankings, however problematic they may be, over time can see changes in the way golf has been viewed and changes in how players value different course attributes and styles of architecture.

Until now, there hasn’t been an easily searchable and viewable way to explore the history of these rankings. Golf Digest and Golf Magazine do not make their data easily available and their data visualizations are practically nil. Visualizations and infographics are critical in allowing us to track trends over time, make links and associations, and generate clusters of similar courses.

Typos and incorrect information are almost assured; indeed, there is sometimes conflicting or missing information even within the same publication. Please feel free to send over corrections, fixes and suggestions to golfcourserankings@gmail.com.

Without further ado…

Pebble Beach Pebble Beach, CA 1919 7 7 7

In both publications, the top 10 is rarefied air that has been occupied almost exclusively by a small number of classic courses built during golf’s “golden age” of design. The position of these tracks has not just been lofty, but also remarkably durable:

  • Pine Valley (top 2 in every ranking in both publications)
  • Cypress Point (top 5 in every ranking)
  • Augusta National (top 5 in every ranking)
  • Shinnecock Hills (top 6 in every ranking)
  • Pebble Beach (top 7 in every ranking)
  • Oakmont (top 8 in every ranking since 1993)
  • Merion (top 8 in every ranking since 1995)

Golf Magazine’s ratings have been especially stable (ossified?) at the top - Pine Valley and Cypress Point have been ranked #1 and #2, respectively, in every edition since the first publication in 1991.

With the exception of Pebble Beach, membership rolls at these courses are populated by captains of industry and they are nearly impossible to get on for the average golfer. Interestingly, not all are tournament-ready - Pine Valley has never hosted professional events, Cypress Point pulled out of the Bing Crosby Clambake more than 30 years ago, and Merion only recently returned to the major championship rota - but the rest are current and former hosts of some of the most renowned and important competitions.

One noteworthy development in this largely static grouping is Golf Magazine putting Augusta National on notice with a column disparaging the club’s recent design changes. Is Augusta’s perennial top 5 streak about to end? More importantly, like the Old Course at St. Andrews, are technological changes making these blue bloods obsolete for PGA Tour pros? (The answer is yes…)


The new (and newly revitalized) blue bloods

Course Location Year Designed Golf Digest Golf Magazine Average
National Golf Links Southampton, NY 1911 8 5 6.5
Sand Hills Mullen, NE 1995 9 9 9
Fishers Island Fishers Island, NY 1926 10 11 10.5
Friar’s Head Baiting Hollow, NY 2002 15 21 18

Like high society in real life, entry into the top echelons from the outside is rare but not impossible. Three courses have made a move into the top 10, two by staging sensational comebacks and the other by single-handedly changing the course of golf course architecture in the new millennium. National was once ranked #56 by Golf Digest and #26 by Golf Magazine but is now at #5 and #8, respectively, while Fishers Island, currently #10 and #11, was out of the top 100 altogether in Golf Digest as recently as 1999.

At #9 in both rankings, Sand Hills’ standing is perhaps the most remarkable on the entire list. The highly influential 1995 Coore/Crenshaw design is more than 60 years newer than the second-youngest top 10 course (Augusta National, 1933) and it is the only course located between Oakmont on the east and Monterey on the west. Friar’s Head, another Coore/Crenshaw collaboration, is a borderline case for the blue blood label but deserves kudos for breaking into the top 15 in Golf Digest.

The courses in this gorup have been mainstays in in the top 20 in one or the other of the two rankings, but they have consistently been placed one notch below the blue bloods. As before, there is a rough 50/50 split between major championship venues and clubs that have shunned the attention and inconvenience that tournaments bring.

Of course anyone would love to belong to clubs like these, but the trend lines are undeniable. Will the negative movement continue or plateau? What’s causing the slide? If a problem can be identified, is it fixable, and if so, for how much money and time? Should members even care? It’s easy to say they shouldn’t, but it’s a tough pill to swallow, and bad for business, when your course drops 20, 30, or more places in the rankings table.

All the while, ghosts of magazines past haunt club boards:

  • Shoal Creek, once ranked #11, out of both rankings
  • Long Cove, once ranked #19, out of both rankings
  • Laurel Valley, once ranked #22, out of both rankings
  • Jupiter Hills, once ranked #23, out of both rankings
  • Black Diamond Ranch, once ranked #24, out of both rankings


Returning to glory

Course Location Year Designed Golf Digest Golf Magazine Average
Chicago Wheaton, IL 1894 14 12 13

Bethpage (Black) Farmingdale, NY 1936 37 23 30

While a host of old-line courses have been muscled out of the top third of the charts, these clubs have been rewarded for renovation work by trendy architects and/or publicity bumps after hosting major amateur and professional events. This list of comeback kids is not a long one even if you add National, Fishers Island, or the small number of other classic courses that have managed to make moves back into the top half of the rankings.

All of them were designed in the 1920s and earlier except Peachtree, which gets honorary “golden age” status from the Bobby Jones connection.

Good news, comrades! Not all of the top 100 is stacked with stuffy, expensive private clubs - there are also some stuffy, expensive public courses as well. But remember, $400 for a round of golf is a hell of a lot less expensive than $100,000 for initiation fees.

The Bandon group is obviously the #1 target here, but after that I would set up shop at Bethpage, the unholy union of Pine Valley and the DMV.

Interestingly, every public course ranked by Golf Digest is ranked by Golf Magazine but not vice versa. It’s one thing to sniff your nose at Streamsong or Torrey Pines, but Pasatiempo?

The Fazio aesthetic represents the clearest difference between the two magazines. Golf Digest loves it, Golf Magazine doesn’t. Alotian was once #14 in Golf Digest (now #31) and is unranked in Golf Magazine, with Gozzer Ranch about to meet a similar fate. Props to anyone who has actually heard of all of these courses, let alone played them.
